[{"location":"migrate-sockets/#Migrating-from-Sockets-to-Reseau","page":"Sockets Migration Guide","title":"Migrating from Sockets to Reseau","text":"If you are using Julia's stdlib Sockets, the main conceptual change is that Reseau makes transport layers explicit instead of forcing everything through one untyped socket surface.\n\nThe payoff is better deadlines, clearer address handling, integrated TLS, and a stack that matches what HTTP.jl 2.0 now uses underneath.","category":"section"},{"location":"migrate-sockets/#Quick-Mapping","page":"Sockets Migration Guide","title":"Quick Mapping","text":"Sockets Reseau\nlisten(ip\"127.0.0.1\", port) Reseau.TCP.listen(Reseau.TCP.loopback_addr(port))\nconnect(ip\"127.0.0.1\", port) Reseau.TCP.connect(Reseau.TCP.loopback_addr(port))\nconnect(\"example.com\", port) Reseau.HostResolvers.connect(\"tcp\", \"example.com:$port\")\naccept(server) Reseau.TCP.accept!(listener)\nclose(sock) Reseau.TCP.close!(conn)\ngetsockname(sock) Reseau.TCP.local_addr(conn)\ngetpeername(sock) Reseau.TCP.remote_addr(conn)\nexternal TLS wrapper Reseau.TLS.connect, Reseau.TLS.listen, Reseau.TLS.client, Reseau.TLS.server","category":"section"},{"location":"migrate-sockets/#The-Two-Most-Common-Ports","page":"Sockets Migration Guide","title":"The Two Most Common Ports","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"migrate-sockets/#1.-Simple-TCP-server","page":"Sockets Migration Guide","title":"1. Simple TCP server","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"migrate-sockets/#Sockets","page":"Sockets Migration Guide","title":"Sockets","text":"using Sockets\n\nserver = listen(ip\"127.0.0.1\", 9000)\nsock = accept(server)","category":"section"},{"location":"migrate-sockets/#Reseau","page":"Sockets Migration Guide","title":"Reseau","text":"using Reseau\n\nlistener = Reseau.TCP.listen(Reseau.TCP.loopback_addr(9000))\nconn = Reseau.TCP.accept!(listener)","category":"section"},{"location":"migrate-sockets/#2.-Hostname-based-client-dial","page":"Sockets Migration Guide","title":"2. Hostname-based client dial","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"migrate-sockets/#Sockets-2","page":"Sockets Migration Guide","title":"Sockets","text":"using Sockets\n\nsock = connect(\"example.com\", 443)","category":"section"},{"location":"migrate-sockets/#Reseau-2","page":"Sockets Migration Guide","title":"Reseau","text":"using Reseau\n\nconn = Reseau.HostResolvers.connect(\"tcp\", \"example.com:443\")","category":"section"},{"location":"migrate-sockets/#Deadlines-Are-First-Class","page":"Sockets Migration Guide","title":"Deadlines Are First-Class","text":"This is one of the biggest quality-of-life improvements over Sockets.\n\nusing Reseau\n\nconn = Reseau.HostResolvers.connect(\"tcp\", \"example.com:443\")\nReseau.TCP.set_read_deadline!(conn, time_ns() + 5_000_000_000)\n\nInstead of managing ad hoc task timeouts around blocking socket calls, the deadline is attached to the connection itself.","category":"section"},{"location":"migrate-sockets/#Shutdown-Is-Explicit","page":"Sockets Migration Guide","title":"Shutdown Is Explicit","text":"Half-closing is exposed directly:\n\nReseau.TCP.close_write!(conn)\nReseau.TCP.close_read!(conn)\n\nThat is a better migration target than reaching for low-level shutdown syscalls.","category":"section"},{"location":"migrate-sockets/#TLS-No-Longer-Lives-Somewhere-Else","page":"Sockets Migration Guide","title":"TLS No Longer Lives Somewhere Else","text":"With Sockets, TLS usually meant another package layered on top. With Reseau, TLS is part of the same stack:\n\nusing Reseau\n\ntls = Reseau.TLS.connect(\n    \"tcp\",\n    \"example.com:443\";\n    verify_peer=true,\n    alpn_protocols=[\"h2\", \"http/1.1\"],\n)\n\nFor servers:\n\ncfg = Reseau.TLS.Config(cert_file=\"server.crt\", key_file=\"server.key\")\nlistener = Reseau.TLS.listen(\"tcp\", \"127.0.0.1:8443\", cfg)","category":"section"},{"location":"migrate-sockets/#What-to-Change-in-Real-Code","page":"Sockets Migration Guide","title":"What to Change in Real Code","text":"Replace direct Sockets.connect(host, port) calls with HostResolvers.connect(\"tcp\", \"host:port\").\nReplace direct listen/accept loops with TCP.listen + TCP.accept!.\nReplace manual timeout wrappers with connection deadlines.\nMove TLS setup onto Reseau.TLS.Config and Reseau.TLS.connect/listen.\nUpdate any code that expected raw Sockets.TCPSocket internals; Reseau uses its own TCP.Conn and TLS.Conn types.","category":"section"},{"location":"migrate-sockets/#Benefits-of-Porting","page":"Sockets Migration Guide","title":"Benefits of Porting","text":"Better deadline and readiness behavior\nClearer address and hostname handling\nTLS integrated into the same stack\nThe same transport semantics used by HTTP.jl 2.0\nA package boundary that makes plain TCP, resolved TCP, and TLS easier to test in isolation","category":"section"},{"location":"tls/#TLS","page":"TLS","title":"TLS","text":"Reseau.TLS is the TLS layer that wraps Reseau.TCP connections and listeners. It uses a Go-style split between reusable configuration and per-connection state.","category":"section"},{"location":"tls/#Core-Types","page":"TLS","title":"Core Types","text":"Reseau.TLS.Config\nReseau.TLS.Conn\nReseau.TLS.Listener\nReseau.TLS.ClientAuthMode\n\nImportant error types:\n\nReseau.TLS.ConfigError\nReseau.TLS.TLSError\nReseau.TLS.TLSHandshakeTimeoutError","category":"section"},{"location":"tls/#Client-Connections","page":"TLS","title":"Client Connections","text":"The easiest path is Reseau.TLS.connect:\n\nusing Reseau\n\nconn = Reseau.TLS.connect(\n    \"tcp\",\n    \"example.com:443\";\n    verify_peer=true,\n    alpn_protocols=[\"h2\", \"http/1.1\"],\n)\n\nIf you already have a Reseau.TCP.Conn, wrap it with Reseau.TLS.client:\n\nusing Reseau\n\ntcp = Reseau.HostResolvers.connect(\"tcp\", \"example.com:443\")\ncfg = Reseau.TLS.Config(alpn_protocols=[\"h2\", \"http/1.1\"])\ntls = Reseau.TLS.client(tcp, cfg)\nReseau.TLS.handshake!(tls)","category":"section"},{"location":"tls/#Server-Listeners","page":"TLS","title":"Server Listeners","text":"Construct a reusable Config, then build a TLS listener:\n\nusing Reseau\n\ncfg = Reseau.TLS.Config(\n    cert_file=\"server.crt\",\n    key_file=\"server.key\",\n    alpn_protocols=[\"h2\", \"http/1.1\"],\n)\n\nlistener = Reseau.TLS.listen(\"tcp\", \"127.0.0.1:8443\", cfg)\nconn = Reseau.TLS.accept!(listener)\n\nAccepted connections are returned in lazy-handshake form, just like Go's crypto/tls.","category":"section"},{"location":"tls/#Configuration-Highlights","page":"TLS","title":"Configuration Highlights","text":"Useful Config keywords include:\n\nserver_name\nverify_peer\nclient_auth\ncert_file\nkey_file\nca_file\nclient_ca_file\nalpn_protocols\nhandshake_timeout_ns\nmin_version\nmax_version","category":"section"},{"location":"tls/#Operational-Notes","page":"TLS","title":"Operational Notes","text":"Deadline handling stays aligned with the underlying transport.\nserver_name is inferred from dial targets when possible.\nALPN is the key bridge between Reseau and HTTP.jl's HTTP/2 behavior.\nThis is the layer to configure certificates and peer verification; HTTP.jl should receive an already-prepared listener or connection policy.","category":"section"},{"location":"reference/#API-Reference","page":"API Reference","title":"API Reference","text":"Reseau keeps its public surface module-qualified. That is intentional: it makes the layer boundaries obvious.","category":"section"},{"location":"reference/#Reseau.TCP","page":"API Reference","title":"Reseau.TCP","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"reference/#Address-constructors","page":"API Reference","title":"Address constructors","text":"Reseau.TCP.SocketAddrV4\nReseau.TCP.SocketAddrV6\nReseau.TCP.loopback_addr\nReseau.TCP.any_addr\nReseau.TCP.loopback_addr6\nReseau.TCP.any_addr6","category":"section"},{"location":"reference/#Connections-and-listeners","page":"API Reference","title":"Connections and listeners","text":"Reseau.TCP.connect\nReseau.TCP.listen\nReseau.TCP.accept!\nReseau.TCP.close!\nReseau.TCP.close_read!\nReseau.TCP.close_write!","category":"section"},{"location":"reference/#Deadlines-and-socket-options","page":"API Reference","title":"Deadlines and socket options","text":"Reseau.TCP.set_deadline!\nReseau.TCP.set_read_deadline!\nReseau.TCP.set_write_deadline!\nReseau.TCP.set_nodelay!\nReseau.TCP.set_keepalive!","category":"section"},{"location":"reference/#Address-inspection","page":"API Reference","title":"Address inspection","text":"Reseau.TCP.local_addr\nReseau.TCP.remote_addr\nReseau.TCP.addr","category":"section"},{"location":"reference/#Reseau.HostResolvers","page":"API Reference","title":"Reseau.HostResolvers","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"reference/#Address-parsing-and-lookup","page":"API Reference","title":"Address parsing and lookup","text":"Reseau.HostResolvers.join_host_port\nReseau.HostResolvers.split_host_port\nReseau.HostResolvers.parse_port\nReseau.HostResolvers.lookup_port\nReseau.HostResolvers.resolve_tcp_addr\nReseau.HostResolvers.resolve_tcp_addrs","category":"section"},{"location":"reference/#Dial/listen-helpers","page":"API Reference","title":"Dial/listen helpers","text":"Reseau.HostResolvers.connect\nReseau.HostResolvers.listen\nReseau.HostResolvers.HostResolver","category":"section"},{"location":"reference/#Resolver-helpers","page":"API Reference","title":"Resolver helpers","text":"Reseau.HostResolvers.ResolverPolicy\nReseau.HostResolvers.SystemResolver\nReseau.HostResolvers.StaticResolver\nReseau.HostResolvers.CachingResolver\nReseau.HostResolvers.SingleflightResolver","category":"section"},{"location":"reference/#Reseau.TLS","page":"API Reference","title":"Reseau.TLS","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"reference/#Main-types","page":"API Reference","title":"Main types","text":"Reseau.TLS.Config\nReseau.TLS.Conn\nReseau.TLS.Listener\nReseau.TLS.ClientAuthMode","category":"section"},{"location":"reference/#Client-and-server-setup","page":"API Reference","title":"Client and server setup","text":"Reseau.TLS.connect\nReseau.TLS.listen\nReseau.TLS.client\nReseau.TLS.server\nReseau.TLS.accept!\nReseau.TLS.handshake!","category":"section"},{"location":"reference/#Lifecycle-and-inspection","page":"API Reference","title":"Lifecycle and inspection","text":"Reseau.TLS.close!\nReseau.TLS.addr","category":"section"},{"location":"reference/#Errors","page":"API Reference","title":"Errors","text":"Reseau.TLS.ConfigError\nReseau.TLS.TLSError\nReseau.TLS.TLSHandshakeTimeoutError","category":"section"},{"location":"reference/#Package-Boundary-Note","page":"API Reference","title":"Package Boundary Note","text":"HTTP-related APIs are intentionally no longer part of Reseau. Use HTTP.jl for:\n\nrequest/response handling\nHTTP clients and servers\nWebSockets\nHPACK and HTTP/2","category":"section"},{"location":"#Reseau.jl","page":"Home","title":"Reseau.jl","text":"Reseau.jl is the lower-level networking stack that now sits under the extracted HTTP.jl 2.0 package.\n\nAfter the split, Reseau owns:\n\nevent loop and poller behavior\nnon-blocking socket operations\nTCP connection and listener types\nhost parsing and resolution\nTLS connections and listeners\n\nIf you want HTTP, WebSockets, SSE, or HTTP/2, use HTTP.jl on top of Reseau.","category":"section"},{"location":"#Installation","page":"Home","title":"Installation","text":"using Pkg\nPkg.add(\"Reseau\")\n\nFor development from a local checkout:\n\nusing Pkg\nPkg.develop(path=\"/path/to/Reseau.jl\")","category":"section"},{"location":"#Package-Shape","page":"Home","title":"Package Shape","text":"The public surface is intentionally module-qualified:\n\nReseau.TCP for concrete-address TCP work\nReseau.HostResolvers for string-address resolution and dialing\nReseau.TLS for TLS clients and listeners\n\nThis makes it clearer which layer owns what, and mirrors the way Go splits transport, name resolution, and TLS responsibilities.","category":"section"},{"location":"#Quick-Start","page":"Home","title":"Quick Start","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"#Direct-address-TCP","page":"Home","title":"Direct-address TCP","text":"using Reseau\n\nlistener = Reseau.TCP.listen(Reseau.TCP.loopback_addr(9000))\nconn = Reseau.TCP.accept!(listener)","category":"section"},{"location":"#String-address-TCP","page":"Home","title":"String-address TCP","text":"using Reseau\n\nconn = Reseau.HostResolvers.connect(\"tcp\", \"example.com:443\")","category":"section"},{"location":"#TLS","page":"Home","title":"TLS","text":"using Reseau\n\nconn = Reseau.TLS.connect(\n    \"tcp\",\n    \"example.com:443\";\n    alpn_protocols=[\"h2\", \"http/1.1\"],\n)","category":"section"},{"location":"#Why-Use-Reseau","page":"Home","title":"Why Use Reseau","text":"Deadlines and blocking behavior are explicit and testable.\nString-address dialing and concrete-address dialing are both first-class.\nTLS is part of the same stack instead of an afterthought layered over a different transport abstraction.\nHTTP.jl 2.0 now uses this exact stack, so transport semantics stay aligned across the ecosystem.","category":"section"},{"location":"#Reading-Guide","page":"Home","title":"Reading Guide","text":"Read TCP and Resolution for the main connection/listener APIs.\nRead TLS for client/server TLS configuration.\nRead Sockets Migration Guide if you are porting from Julia's stdlib Sockets.","category":"section"},{"location":"tcp/#TCP-and-Resolution","page":"TCP and Resolution","title":"TCP and Resolution","text":"Reseau splits TCP work into two layers:\n\nReseau.TCP for concrete socket addresses\nReseau.HostResolvers for string-address parsing, host resolution, and timeout-aware dialing","category":"section"},{"location":"tcp/#Reseau.TCP","page":"TCP and Resolution","title":"Reseau.TCP","text":"Use Reseau.TCP when you already know the exact address family and endpoint you want.","category":"section"},{"location":"tcp/#Address-Types","page":"TCP and Resolution","title":"Address Types","text":"Reseau.TCP.SocketAddrV4\nReseau.TCP.SocketAddrV6\nReseau.TCP.loopback_addr\nReseau.TCP.any_addr\nReseau.TCP.loopback_addr6\nReseau.TCP.any_addr6","category":"section"},{"location":"tcp/#Connections-and-Listeners","page":"TCP and Resolution","title":"Connections and Listeners","text":"using Reseau\n\naddr = Reseau.TCP.loopback_addr(9000)\nlistener = Reseau.TCP.listen(addr; backlog=128, reuseaddr=true)\nconn = Reseau.TCP.accept!(listener)\n\nClient connections are just as direct:\n\nusing Reseau\n\nconn = Reseau.TCP.connect(Reseau.TCP.loopback_addr(9000))\nwrite(conn, collect(codeunits(\"hello\")))\nbuf = Vector{UInt8}(undef, 5)\nread!(conn, buf)","category":"section"},{"location":"tcp/#Deadlines-and-Shutdown","page":"TCP and Resolution","title":"Deadlines and Shutdown","text":"These are important differences from Sockets:\n\nReseau.TCP.set_deadline!(conn, deadline_ns)\nReseau.TCP.set_read_deadline!(conn, deadline_ns)\nReseau.TCP.set_write_deadline!(conn, deadline_ns)\nReseau.TCP.close_read!(conn)\nReseau.TCP.close_write!(conn)","category":"section"},{"location":"tcp/#Address-Inspection","page":"TCP and Resolution","title":"Address Inspection","text":"Reseau.TCP.local_addr(conn)\nReseau.TCP.remote_addr(conn)\nReseau.TCP.addr(listener)","category":"section"},{"location":"tcp/#Reseau.HostResolvers","page":"TCP and Resolution","title":"Reseau.HostResolvers","text":"Use HostResolvers when you want the package to handle host parsing and resolution for you.","category":"section"},{"location":"tcp/#Common-Entry-Points","page":"TCP and Resolution","title":"Common Entry Points","text":"Reseau.HostResolvers.connect(\"tcp\", \"example.com:443\")\nReseau.HostResolvers.connect(\"example.com:443\")\nReseau.HostResolvers.listen(\"tcp\", \"127.0.0.1:9000\")\nReseau.HostResolvers.resolve_tcp_addr\nReseau.HostResolvers.resolve_tcp_addrs\nReseau.HostResolvers.lookup_port\nReseau.HostResolvers.join_host_port\nReseau.HostResolvers.split_host_port","category":"section"},{"location":"tcp/#Example","page":"TCP and Resolution","title":"Example","text":"using Reseau\n\nlistener = Reseau.HostResolvers.listen(\"tcp\", \"127.0.0.1:9000\")\nconn = Reseau.HostResolvers.connect(\"tcp\", \"127.0.0.1:9000\")\npeer = Reseau.TCP.accept!(listener)","category":"section"},{"location":"tcp/#Resolution-Policies","page":"TCP and Resolution","title":"Resolution Policies","text":"HostResolvers also owns the higher-level resolution helpers:\n\nResolverPolicy\nSystemResolver\nStaticResolver\nCachingResolver\nSingleflightResolver\nHostResolver\n\nThese are the right tools when you want to tune IPv4/IPv6 preference, cache lookups, or control resolution behavior explicitly.","category":"section"}]
